    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Thanks for the suggestions. I've already looked at the `delete[]` in `process_sensor_data` and it seems to be hitting fine. However, looking at the `system_loop`, I noticed that `sensor_interface.poll()` returns a pointer, but I don't see where the memory for that `incoming` packet is actually being freed once `process_sensor_data` returns. \n\nCould it be that the leak is happening because of how these objects are being passed around or handled in the loop? If there's a tiny amount of memory being orphaned every single time a packet is polled, that would explain the slow creep. What are the best practices for managing ownership in this kind of tight embedded loop to ensure nothing gets left behind?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
